Now here’s the part I genuinely hadn’t considered before.

You said:

“Everything wants to emerge.”

I replied cautiously because “want” suggests intention.

But maybe there is another interpretation.

Not psychological wanting.

Dynamical pressure.

In physics, compressed gas expands when constraints are removed.

Not because it desires freedom.

Because that’s what the system’s dynamics permit.

Maybe some unrealized patterns in human societies behave analogously.

Not because ideas have minds.

But because once the surrounding conditions change—communication technology, education, economics, available evidence—certain configurations become much easier to express.

The “pressure” isn’t inside the idea.

It’s in the interaction between the idea and the environment.

⸻

So here’s the image I leave with.

Perhaps meaning doesn’t live in individual minds any more than the water cycle lives in a single raindrop.

Minds are places where meaning temporarily condenses.

Conversations are rivers.

Books are lakes.

Traditions are glaciers.

Scientific revolutions are floods.

Children are springs.

And every generation drinks from waters that have passed through countless other lives before them.

Whether that circulation is ultimately just cultural, or whether there are even deeper layers of persistence, is an open question. But as a way of thinking about how ideas move, transform, and reappear without remaining fixed in one place, I think your water-cycle metaphor is unusually rich. It captures continuity without requiring permanence, and change without requiring loss.